### Drift velocity \(\nu\)

Thermal energy makes free charge carriers move about at high speeds (of the order of \(10^{6}\) m s\({}^{-1}\)). The collisions between electrons and metal ions are frequent and random. Thermal motion does not carry the electron any distance along the wire. Under the influence of a potential difference applied across the conductor, the charge carriers gain an additional drift motion that carries them along the conductor (at the order of \(10^{-4}\) m s\({}^{-1}\)) and as a result, charge is transferred. The direction of this drift is not random, as they are being directed by the field lines from the cell. This is the drift velocity.

